04020nam a22006975i 9783110730074DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022941623  a97831107300747 a10.1515/97831107300742doi  a(DE-B1597)572911  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0110002bisacsh1 aKubozono, Haruo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWord and Sentence Prosody :bThe Endangered Dialect of Koshikijima Japanese /cHaruo Kubozono. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (XI, 224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPhonology and Phonetics [PP] ,x1861-4191 ;v3100tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tList of abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Introduction to Japanese phonology -- t2 Typological features of KosJ word prosody -- t3 Emergence of a secondary H Tone -- t4 Syllable and accent -- t5 Postlexical deletion of lexical H Tone -- t6 Question and vocative prosody -- t7 Other aspects of sentence prosody -- t8 Summary and prospect -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first comprehensive work on word and sentence prosody in Koshikijima Japanese, a dialect of Japanese not fully documented in the literature. It is an endangered dialect spoken by about 2,000 speakers on a small southern island in Japan. Being separated from mainland dialects by the sea, this dialect exhibits unique prosodic features not shared by other Japanese dialects. It also exhibits considerable regional variations among the ten or more small villages that were isolated from each other until recently.Based on the author’s fieldwork, the book analyzes word accent and intonation, the two linguistic areas in which this endangered dialect exhibits unique features and remarkable regional variations within itself. They include the emergence and development of a secondary H tone, postlexical deletion of the primary H tone, and the L boundary tone in question and vocative intonation. These phenomena bear crucially on general issues in prosody, including postlexical tonal neutralizations, competitions between lexical and postlexical tones, and the number of tones that a syllable can maximally bear. The book thus demonstrates the relevance of studying an endangered language/dialect in general linguistic contexts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 4aBedrohte Sprache. 4aKoshikijima. 4aProsodie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Phonetics & Phonology.2bisacsh  aEndangered Language.  aKoshikijima Japanese.  aSentence Prosody.  aWord Prosody.0 cEPUBz97831107301280 cprintz978311073505540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311073007440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110730074423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110730074/original  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK